############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ Context()->variables->add(n => "Real", a => "Real", b => "Real");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Consider the following puzzle:
You have a rectangular chocolate bar, made up of [`n`] identical squares of chocolate. You can take such a bar and break it along any row or column. How many times will you have to break the bar to reduce it to [`n`] single chocolate squares?
At first, this question might seem impossible. Perhaps we meant to ask for the _smallest_ number of breaks needed. Let's investigate.
END_PGML
############################################################ # Scaffold ############################################################ Scaffold::Begin(numbered => 1,is_open => "correct_or_first_incorrect",can_open => when_previous_correct,);
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML Suppose you started with a [`1\times 3`] bar. How many breaks would you need to reduce it to single squares?
[_]{2}{5}
END_PGML
Section::End();
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML If you had a [`1\times 4`] bar, how many breaks are required?
[_]{3}{5}
If you had 4 squares arranged in a [`2\times 2`] square, your first break would require you to break the chocolate into two [`1 \times 2`] bars. Then each of these would require [_]{1}{5} more break(s), for a total of [_]{3}{5} breaks to go from the [`2\times 2`] to single squares.
END_PGML
Section::End();
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML A [`6`]-square bar could either be a [`1 \times 6`] bar, requiring [_]{5}{5} breaks, or a [`2 \times 3`] bar.
There are two ways to proceed now. a. Break the bar into two [`1 \times 3`] bars, each requiring [_]{2}{5} more breaks, for a total of [_]{5}{5} breaks.
a. Break the bar into a [`1\times 2`] bar and a [`2 \times 2`] bar. The [`1 \times 2`] bar takes [_]{1}{5} more break(s) and the [`2 \times 2`] bar takes [_]{3}{5} more break(s), for a total of [_]{5}{5} breaks.
END_PGML
Section::End();
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML Based on the above data, what should our conjecture be for the number of breaks to reduce an [`n`]-square bar to single squares, in terms of [`n\text{?}`]
It will take [_]{Compute('n-1')}{10} breaks to reduce an [`n`]-square bar to single squares.
END_PGML
Section::End();
############################################################ # Section ############################################################ Section::Begin("");
BEGIN_PGML Do we believe this? Suppose you used one break to reduce the bar into two smaller bars, with [`a`] and [`b`] squares respectively. If the conjecture is correct, how many more breaks will it take to reduce the size [`a`] bar?
[_]{Compute('a-1')}{10}
How many more breaks will it take to reduce the size [`b`] bar?
[_]{Compute('b-1')}{10}
How many breaks is this all together, in terms of [`a`] and [`b\text{,}`] including the initial break?
[_]{Compute('1+a-1+b-1')}{10}
But what is [`a+b\text{?}`] We got [`a`] and [`b`] by breaking the [`n`] squares in two pieces, so [`a+b = `][_]{Compute('n')}{5}. This gives us a total number of breaks as [_]{Compute('n-1')}{10}.
END_PGML
Section::End();
Scaffold::End();
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
