BEGIN_PGML Write out all function [`f: \{1,2\} \to \{a,b,c,d\}`] (in two-line notation).
How many functions are there?
[_]{16}{10}
How many are surjective?
[_]{0}{10}
How many are injective?
[_]{12}{10}
How many are bijective?
[_]{0}{10}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION There are 16 functions: you have a choice of four outputs for [`f(1)\text{,}`] and for each, you have four choices for the output [`f(2)\text{.}`] Of these functions, 12 are injective, 0 are surjective, and 0 are both (i.e., bijective):
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{a\amp a} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{b \amp b} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{c \amp c} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{d \amp d} ```]
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{a\amp b} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{a \amp c} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{a \amp d} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{b \amp c} ```]
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{b \amp a} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{c \amp a} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{d \amp a} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{c \amp b} ```]
[```\newcommand{\amp}{&} f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{b \amp d} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{d \amp b} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{c \amp d} \quad f = \twoline{1 \amp 2}{d \amp c} ```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
